You need to check if a number is simultaneously 7-safe, 11-safe, and 13-safe. A number \( n \) is \( p \)-safe if it differs in absolute value by more than 2 from all multiples of \( p \). To check for \( p \)-safety, we need to check if \( n \) is not within 2 units of any multiple of \( p \). That means we need to check if \( n \) is not congruent to \( 0, 1, p-2, \) or \( p-1 \mod p \). The constraints for \( n \) being 7-safe, 11-safe, and 13-safe can be formulated as:
\[ n \mod 7 \neq 0, 1, 5, 6 \]
\[ n \mod 11 \neq 0, 1, 9, 10 \]
\[ n \mod 13 \neq 0, 1, 11, 12 \]
<end think>
```python
def is_p_safe(n, p):
    multiples = {0, 1, p-2, p-1}
    multiples = {i % p for i in multiples}
    return n % p not in multiples

def is_safe(n):
    return is_p_safe(n, 7) and is_p_safe(n, 11) and is_p_safe(n, 13)

count = 0
for n in range(1, 10001):
    if is_safe(n):
        count += 1

print(count)
```
```output
870
```
